The '''Big Bang UK Young Scientists and Engineers Fair''' is the United Kingdom’s largest celebration of [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] (science, technology, engineering and maths) for young people, and is the largest youth event in the [[UK]]. The fair takes place annually in March. It is led by [[EngineeringUK]] in partnership with over 200 organisations across government, industry, education and the wider science and engineering community.

The Big Bang programme exists to bring science and engineering to life for young people. The Big Bang celebrates and raises the profile of young people’s achievements in science and engineering and encourages more young people to take part in science, technology, engineering and maths initiatives with support from their parents and teachers.

Big Bang Near Me events take place across the UK to enable young people to discover close to home the exciting and rewarding science and engineering careers that their science and maths subjects can lead to.

In 2012, the Big Bang Fair was hosted in the [[National Exhibition Centre]] in Birmingham. An all-girls team of pupils from a state school in the Highlands- Alness Academy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=6243101 |title=Ace of clubs is on shaky ground |first=Jean |last=McLeish |website=Tes.co.uk |date=2012-06-01 |accessdate=2016-07-15}}</ref> were awarded the prestigious title of UK Young Engineers of the Year for their work on health and safety prototypes to be used in Haiti, which had recently suffered major earthquake damage alongside an outbreak of cholera. The six girls were Josie Tolliday, Emma Roddick, Cassie Armstrong, Meg Beattie, Holly Henderson and Kayleigh MacDonald.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.highland.gov.uk/news/article/6010/alness_academy_team_becomes_young_engineers_club_of_the_year_2012 |title=Alness Academy team becomes Young Engineers Club of the Year 2012 |website=Highland.gov.uk |date=2012-03-19 |accessdate=2016-07-15}}</ref>

The all-girl team have continued to excel in their extra-curricular activities. Cassie Armstrong is now an elected Member of Scottish Youth Parliament; Emma Roddick went on to become Donald Dewar Debater of the Year;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://speakupscotland.squarespace.com/storage/Programme%20for%20Big%20Balloon%20Debate%20Final.pdf |format=PDF |title=Big Balloon Debate Final |website=Speakupscotland.squarespace.com |date=2012-03-30 |accessdate=2016-07-15}}</ref> Kayleigh MacDonald has been successful in dance competition Rock Challenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ross-shirejournal.co.uk/News/Alness-pupils-rock-judges-with-their-dance-moves-22022012.htm |title=Alness pupils rock judges with their dance moves |publisher=Ross-shire Journal |date=2012-02-24 |accessdate=2016-07-15}}</ref>

== Criticism ==
The Big Bang Fair has been criticised by NGOs such as the Campaign Against the Arms Trade<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caat.org.uk/campaigns/arms-trade-out/science/big-bang-fair|title=CAAT - Campaigns - Arms Trade Out! - Science - Big Bang Fair|website=Campaign Against Arms Trade|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref> and Friends of the Earth due to the heavy involvement of arms manufacturers and fossil fuel companies at the event. The event has also been described as being led by the PR of companies rather than education, and for presenting a "distorted view of the value of science" in reference to the involvement of arms manufacturers and oil companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/political-science/2013/mar/18/science-policy1|title=The Big Bang Fair: a depressing vision of science and engineering|last=Bell|first=Alice|date=2013-03-18|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/political-science/2014/mar/26/the-big-bang-fair-puts-pr-above-education|title=The Big Bang Fair puts PR above education|last=Bell|first=Alice|date=2014-03-26|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.themanufacturer.com/articles/big-bang-fair-kicks-off-today-with-thousands-of-students-expected/|title=Big Bang Fair kicks off today with thousands of students expected|last=Brown|first=Tim|date=2014-03-13|work=The Manufacturer|access-date=2018-01-05|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-GB}}</ref>

