{{primary sources|date=May 2013}} {{Infobox_University |image_name = |image_size = |name = School of Chemistry |established = |type = [[public university|Public]] |city = [[Camperdown, New South Wales|Camperdown]] / [[Darlington, New South Wales|Darlington]] |state = [[New South Wales]] |country = [[Australia]] |coordinates = {{coord|-33.887923|151.189538|display=title, inline}} |affiliations = [[University of Sydney]] |students = |staff = |campus = |website = [http://sydney.edu.au/science/chemistry/ sydney.edu.au/science/chemistry] }}
The '''School of Chemistry''' is a constituent body of the [[Sydney Faculty of Science|Faculty of Science]] at the [[University of Sydney]], [[Australia]].
Two [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Laureates]] are associated with the School: [[John Cornforth]] completed his undergraduate degree in the School, graduating in 1938 with First Class Honours and the University Medal; and [[Robert Robinson (organic chemist)|Robert Robinson]] was appointed as the first Professor of Pure and Applied Organic Chemistry at the University in 1912.<ref>http://www.chem.usyd.edu.au/aboutus/laureates.html</ref>
==History== [[File:Liquid_Nitrogen_Tank.JPG|thumb|right|Liquid nitrogen tank outside the Chemistry Building]]
The Chemistry Building, which is the School's main building, is notable in architectural history as one of the first structures in Australia with a [[curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]]. The building was completed in 1956.<ref>http://www.chem.usyd.edu.au/aboutus/aboutusattachments/ChemistryBuildingJME.pdf</ref>
