'''Writing Commons''' (WC) is a [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] [[Open Education Resources|open education resource]] (OER) for college-level writers. Founded in 2008 by [http://joemoxley.org/sites/Joe_Moxley/default.aspx Joseph M. Moxley], a professor of English and the director of the first-year writing program at the [[University of South Florida]], Writing Commons was developed from a highly regarded text into one of the most heavily used open textbooks on the [[World Wide Web|web]].<ref>“[http://writingcommons.org/about/why-writing-commons Why Writing Commons?]” Writing Commons. University of South Florida, N.d. Web.</ref> Following a [[crowdsourcing]] process, Writing Commons now offers an interactive and comprehensive introduction to college-level writing. In 2012, Writing Commons was viewed by over 145,000 unique users for a total of 167,000 users.<ref>“[http://writingcommons.org/about About].” Writing Commons. University of South Florida, N.d. Web.</ref> Writing Commons was developed from ''College Writing Online'' (Longman/Pearson, 2003)<ref>Barton, Matt. Rev. of [http://kairos.technorhetoric.net/8.2/binder.html?reviews/barton/index.htm College Writing Online], by Joseph Moxley. Kairos 8.2 (2003): N.p. Web. 11 Feb. 2013.</ref> a first-year composition textbook written by Joseph Moxley. Awarded the [http://computersandcomposition.candcblog.org/awards/distinguishedbook.htm Distinguished Book Award] by ''Computers and Composition: an International Journal'' in 2004,<ref>“[http://computersandcomposition.candcblog.org/awards/distinguishedbook.htm ''Computers and Composition'' Awards].” ''Computers and Composition: An International Journal''. Elsevier, N.d. Web.</ref> ''College Writing Online'' has since been republished as Writing Commons in an open textbook format. Writing Commons accepts submissions through a strenuous peer-review process. The [http://writingcommons.org/about/editorial-board editorial board] consists of distinguished educators and academics from across the globe. Writing Commons publishes webtexts under a [[Creative Commons]] 3.0 NC ND License.<ref>“[http://writingcommons.org/about About].” Writing Commons. University of South Florida, N.d. Web.</ref>
Writing Commons is currently used as a supplemented text in the first-year writing program at the University of South Florida. The first-year composition program at the University of South Florida, utilizing Writing Commons as a text, was awarded the 2012 [http://www.ncte.org/cccc/awards/writingprogramcert Writing Program Certificate of Excellence] by the [http://www.ncte.org/ National Council of Teachers of English] and the [http://www.ncte.org/cccc Conference on College Composition].<ref>“[http://www.ncte.org/cccc/awards/writingprogramcert CCCC Writing Program Certificate of Excellence].” Conference on College Composition and Communication. NCTE, Sept. 2012. Web.</ref> Writing Commons offers [http://writingcommons.org/open-text (Open) Text], an area devoted to various aspects of writing in college and especially writing on the Web. [http://writingcommons.org/common-comments Common Comments], another partnership with the first-year writing program at the University of South Florida, provides an enhanced peer review commenting platform. The site also supports Common Space, an open area for users to generate blog posts, provide comments, and ask questions.
